    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Casting Al Gore: Think Frasier, Not Chachi</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barry Langman letter likens Al Gore to successful television spinoff, such as Frasier, not to short-lived sequel Joanie Loves Chachi</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Al Gore as Fall Programming,'' by Gail Collins (column, Aug. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Al Gore as Fall Programming,'' by Gail Collins (column, Aug. 18):</p>
        <p>Ms. Collins suggests that Al Gore may be the first episode of ''Joanie Loves Chachi'' to Bill Clinton's ''Happy Days.'' But not every TV spinoff is a weak rehash of a tired original, destined for audience rejection.</p>
        <p>The clear intention of the Democratic National Convention this year -- and the selection of Joseph I. Lieberman as Mr. Gore's running mate -- was to persuade the public that a different supporting cast and a new outlook will enable this second banana to headline a new show successfully.</p>
        <p>Put differently, the goal is to portray Al Gore not as a Chachi but more like a Frasier or a Rhoda or a George Jefferson.</p>
        <p>We will have to keep tuning in to find out whether this casting concept survives the political equivalent of the November ratings sweeps.</p>
        <p>BARRY LANGMAN  New York, Aug. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
